{{Infobox rock |name=Latite |type=Volcanic |image=Latit - Boxberg, Hocheifel.jpg |image caption= Latite from Boxberg, High-Eifel, Germany }} [[Image:Latite nicol parallei.jpg|thumb|[[Photomicrograph]] of [[thin section]] of latite (in plane [[Polarization (waves)|polarised]] light)]] [[Image:Latite nicol incrociati.gif|thumb|[[Photomicrograph]] of [[thin section]] of latite (in cross [[Polarization (waves)|polarised]] light)]] '''Latite''' is an [[igneous rock|igneous]], [[volcanic rock]], with [[aphanitic]]-[[Phenocryst#Classification by phenocryst|aphyric]] to aphyric-[[porphyritic]] texture. Its [[mineral]] assemblage is usually alkali [[feldspar]] and [[plagioclase]] in approximately equal amounts. [[Quartz]] is less than five percent and is absent in a [[feldspathoid]]-bearing latite, and [[olivine]] is absent in a [[quartz]]-bearing latite. When quartz content is greater than five percent the rock is classified as [[quartz latite]].<ref name=IUGS>[http://geology.csupomona.edu/alert/igneous/igclass.htm Classification of Igneous Rocks] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930102012/http://geology.csupomona.edu/alert/igneous/igclass.htm |date=2011-09-30 }}</ref> [[Biotite]], [[hornblende]], [[pyroxene]] and scarce [[olivine]] or [[quartz]] are common accessory minerals.
[[Rhomb porphyry|Rhomb porphyries]] are an unusual variety with gray-white [[porphyritic]] [[Rhombus|rhomb]] shaped [[phenocryst]]s embedded in a very fine grained red-brown [[Matrix (geology)|matrix]]. The composition of rhomb porphyry places it in the [[trachyte]] - latite classification of the [[QAPF diagram]].
Latite is found, for example, as lavas in Bulgaria<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/full/2001CRABS..54c..63G | title=Volcanism in the Momchilgrad Volcanotectonic Depression |author1=Georgiev, V. |author2=Milovanov, P. | journal=Comptes rendus de l'Académie bulgare des Sciences | year=2001 | volume=54 | issue=3 | pages=63–66 | bibcode=2001CRABS..54c..63G}} Retrieved on 5 July 2015.</ref> and as [[Intrusion|intrusive]] [[laccolith]]s and [[Sill (geology)|sills]] in [[South Dakota]], USA.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mrdata.usgs.gov/geology/state/sgmc-unit.php?unit=SDTl%3B0 | title=Latitic Intrusive Rocks | publisher=[[USGS]] | accessdate=5 July 2015}}</ref>
